# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: battery-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:battery-baseball/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:battery-baseball/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:battery-baseball/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1878 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:battery-baseball/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished second in the National League with a record of 37–23, four games behind the Boston Red Caps.
[src:battery-baseball/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] After finishing their first two seasons in the National League in last place, the Reds were hoping for some improvement in the 1878 season.
[src:battery-baseball/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati signed Cal McVey of the Chicago White Stockings to become the team's new third baseman, and new manager.
[src:battery-baseball/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Catcher Deacon White of the Boston Red Caps signed with Cincinnati.
[src:battery-baseball/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White led the National League with a .387 batting average, 103 hits, eleven triples, 49 RBI, and a .545 slugging percentage with the Red Caps in 1877.
[src:battery-baseball/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White also led the National League with 60 RBI while playing for the White Stockings in 1876.
[src:battery-baseball/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] On the mound, 23-year-old Will White was signed by the Reds.
[src:battery-baseball/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White appeared in three games with the Boston Red Caps in 1877, going 2–1 with a 3.00 ERA.
[src:battery-baseball/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Charley Jones had another very solid season with the Reds, as he had a .310 batting average, along with a team high three home runs and 39 RBI.
[src:battery-baseball/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White saw his production slip, however, he still hit .314 with 29 RBI.
[src:battery-baseball/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Player-manager McVey was solid with a .306 average and two home runs along with 28 RBI.
[src:battery-baseball/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White had a spectacular season, going 30–21 with a 1.79 ERA in 468 innings pitched.
[src:battery-baseball/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds opened the season with a six-game winning streak, and stayed hot in their first twenty games, going 15–5, and were sitting in first place in the National League.
[src:battery-baseball/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati then went on a six-game losing streak, falling to 15–11, and out of first place.
[src:battery-baseball/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds never reclaimed first place; however, they finished the season strong, including a nine-game winning streak late in the year, to finish in second place with a 37–23 record, five games behind the first place Boston Red Caps.
[src:battery-baseball/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1879 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:battery-baseball/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished fifth in the National League with a record of 43–37, 14 games behind the Providence Grays.
[src:battery-baseball/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds were hoping to build off a great 1878 season, in which the team finished in second place in the National League with a 37–23 record.
[src:battery-baseball/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] In the off-season, the Reds announced that catcher Deacon White would become the player-manager.
[src:battery-baseball/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati signed Ross Barnes to play shortstop.
[src:battery-baseball/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Barnes had missed most of the 1877 season and all of the 1878 season after falling ill.
[src:battery-baseball/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] In his last full season in 1876, Barnes played with the Chicago White Stockings, and led the NL with a .429 batting average, 138 hits, 126 runs, 38 doubles, and fourteen triples.
[src:battery-baseball/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] King Kelly had a very solid season, hitting .348 with two home runs and 47 RBI, while another youngster, twenty-year-old Buttercup Dickerson, hit .291 with two home runs and a team high 57 RBI.
[src:battery-baseball/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Deacon White rebounded from a poor 1878 season by his standards, as he hit .330 with a homer and 52 RBI.
[src:battery-baseball/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] On the mound, Will White led the NL with 75 starts, as he had a 43–31 record with a 1.99 ERA in his league high 680 innings pitched.
[src:battery-baseball/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati started off hot, as they opened the season with a five-game winning streak.
[src:battery-baseball/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] However, the club lost seven of their next eight games to fall under .500.
[src:battery-baseball/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati had a mediocre 9–9 record after eighteen games, and player-manager Deacon White turned over his managerial duties to Cal McVey, who had been the Reds' player-manager in 1878.
[src:battery-baseball/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati lost the first five games under McVey, however, the team began to play better, and ended the season with a 43–37 record, fifth in the league, and fourteen games behind the first-place Grays.
[src:battery-baseball/1885-buffalo-bisons-season] The **1885 Buffalo Bisons** finished the season with a 38–74 record, good for seventh place in the National League.
[src:battery-baseball/1885-buffalo-bisons-season] As things continued to implode on the field, the team ownership sold the whole franchise to the Detroit Wolverines.
[src:battery-baseball/1885-buffalo-bisons-season] With all their players gone, the team finished out the season with local amateurs filling in.
[src:battery-baseball/1890-new-york-giants-pl-season] The **1890 New York Giants** baseball team was a member of the short lived Players' League.
[src:battery-baseball/1890-new-york-giants-pl-season] They compiled a 74–57 record, good for third place, eight games behind the league champion Boston Reds.
[src:battery-baseball/1890-new-york-giants-pl-season] After the season, the league folded, and the Giants were bought out by their National League New York Giants.
[src:battery-baseball/1890-new-york-giants-pl-season] The Giants were the original tenants of the Polo Grounds stadium that afterwards was occupied by the National League's New York Giants for 66 years.
[src:battery-baseball/1891-new-york-giants-season] The **1891 New York Giants season** was the franchise's ninth season.
[src:battery-baseball/1891-new-york-giants-season] The team finished in third place in the National League with a 71–61 record, 13 games behind the Boston Beaneaters.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] In baseball, the **battery** is the pitcher and the catcher, who may also be called **batterymen**, or **batterymates** in relation to one another.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] The use of the term *battery* in baseball was coined by Henry Chadwick in the 1860s in reference to the firepower of a team's pitching staff and inspired by the artillery batteries then in use in the American Civil War.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] Later, the term evolved to indicate the combined effectiveness of pitcher and catcher.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] Throughout the history of baseball, although teams have typically carried multiple catchers, star pitchers have often preferred the familiarity of working consistently with a single batterymate.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] In the early 20th century, some prominent pitchers were known to have picked their favorite catchers.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] Other successful batteries were Ed Walsh / Billy Sullivan beginning in 1904, along with Walter Johnson / Muddy Ruel and Dazzy Vance / Hank DeBerry both starting in 1923.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] In 1976, several major league pitchers chose their preferred catchers; a notion that had fallen out of practice for some decades.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] For instance, catcher Bob Boone of the Philadelphia Phillies, though one of the best catchers of his day, was replaced with Tim McCarver at the request of pitcher Steve Carlton.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] The Carlton/McCarver combination worked well in 32 out of Carlton's 35 games that season, plus one playoff game.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] The two had previously been batterymates for four years (1966–69) with the St.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] Another battery-by-choice was superstitious rookie pitcher Mark Fidrych who was new to the Detroit Tigers in 1976, insisting on rookie catcher Bruce Kimm behind the plate.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] The Fidrych/Kimm combination started all 29 of Fidrych's 1976 season games.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] The two continued as a battery through 1977.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] Knuckleballers have often preferred pitching to "personal" batterymates due to the difficulty of catching the unusual pitch.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] One notable example was Boston Red Sox pitcher Tim Wakefield and his preferred catcher, Doug Mirabelli.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] , and also hold the record for team wins by a starting battery (213).
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] The below table shows battery-mates that as of September 20, 2022, have appeared in more than 200 starts together since 1914.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] recorded two no-hitters in a span of five days in June 1938.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] The table below lists the battery combinations that share the record for most major league no-hitters (2).
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] (*) Catchers Silver Flint and King Kelly shared catching duties for Corcoran's August 19, 1880 no-hitter.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] The following chart of major league sibling batteries lists pitcher/catcher siblings who played on the same major league team during a single major league season.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] The pair may or may not have performed as a battery in an actual major league game.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] Unique among those listed below are Mort and Walker Cooper, who formed the National League's starting battery at both the 1942 and 1943 Major League Baseball All-Star Games, and also appeared as a battery in the 1942, 1943, and 1944 World Series, the only sibling battery to achieve either feat.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] The battery that appeared in the most games together was Mariano Rivera and Jorge Posada, with 598 games together for the New York Yankees between 1995 and 2011.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] The record for most team wins by a starting battery is 213 by Adam Wainwright and Yadier Molina.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] Red Faber and Ray Schalk, who played together for the Chicago White Sox between 1914 and 1928, recorded the most total innings as a battery (2553.2).
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] Madison Bumgarner and Buster Posey of the San Francisco Giants became the major league's first battery to hit grand slams in the same game when they accomplished the feat on July 13, 2014 against the Arizona Diamondbacks.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] The home run was pitcher Bumgarner's second grand slam of the season (April 11).
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] Pitcher George Stovey and catcher Moses Fleetwood Walker formed the first Black battery in professional baseball history when they teamed up for the 1887 Newark Little Giants of the International Association.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] The tandem recorded ten consecutive wins to begin the season before the Chicago White Stockings refused to take the field on July 15, leading to the league's implementation of the color line.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] Frank Duncan, Jr. and his son, Frank Duncan III, of the 1941 Kansas City Monarchs are thought to be the only father-son battery in major league history.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] In a game on September 7, 2012, former major leaguer Roger Clemens came out of retirement to pitch for the minor league Sugar Land Skeeters of the Atlantic League of Professional Baseball, and formed a battery with his son Koby Clemens.
[src:battery-baseball/battery-baseball] Paul Skenes and Henry Davis of the Pittsburgh Pirates formed the first major league battery where both the pitcher and catcher were selected first overall in their respective draft years, 2023 and 2021.
